Torygg's Legacy: A Long-Form Skyrim TTRPG Campaign
Campaign Premise
In an alternate Skyrim, the Dragonborn exists but his destiny was never triggered. Old Bjorn, a skilled and charismatic fisherman-turned-cart-driver, possesses the soul of a Dragonborn but never attended his execution at Helgen. Without the prophesied hero, dragons are returning, the Dragon Cult is awakening, and Skyrim is descending into civil war.
High King Torygg, recognizing these mounting threats, creates a Royal Charter just before his death to establish "The Skyrim Wardens" - a specialized group to handle supernatural threats that no Jarl's guard can manage.
The players are chosen heroes who must rise to save Skyrim in the absence of prophecy. But they are not alone in this quest. Another hero walks a parallel pathΓÇöthe Rival, whose superior skill and ruthless pragmatism will lead him down a darker road, forcing the party to confront what they themselves might become.

Campaign Structure Overview
Act I: The Freelance Era (Sandbox Phase)
Duration: Indeterminate (until players reach Expert Tier, approximately 4-5 AP)
 Style: Open sandbox with episodic adventures
 Goal: Establish the party as capable heroes with a growing reputation
Act II: The King's Mandate (The Inciting Incident)
Duration: 2-3 sessions
 Style: Narrative pivot with major NPC introductions
 Goal: Induct the party into the Wardens, introduce the Rival and Old Bjorn, then shatter everything with Torygg's death
Act III: The Mortal Limit (Parallel Journeys)
Duration: Multiple sessions (Sessions 9-32 approximately)
 Style: Investigation, escalating combat, and mounting dread
 Goal: Lead both the party and the Rival to discover they cannot win through conventional means
Act IV: The Unwritten Prophecy (The Divergence)
Duration: Multiple sessions (Sessions 33-45 approximately)
 Style: Two distinct paths converging on a final confrontation
 Goal: Force a world-defining choice and deliver the final confrontation with both the Rival and Alduin

Act I: The Freelance Era
Overview
The campaign begins with the party already formed as an independent adventuring company. They take contracts, build their reputation, and advance their skills. This act has no predetermined length - it continues until the party reaches Expert Tier.
Critical Omissions: Old Bjorn is NOT present. The Rival is NOT present. This act is solely about the party's organic growth.
Structure
No fixed endpoint: The main quest trigger is tied to player advancement, not a session count
Player-driven: The party chooses which contracts to pursue
Reputation matters: Track the party's growing fame through their completed quests
The Adventure Pool
Prepare 3-5 complete one-shot adventures. Each should:
Award 1 Advancement Point upon completion
Feature diverse threat types (undead, nature corruption, bandits, etc.)
Be playable in any order
Include complete stat blocks, loot tables, and encounter designs
Confirmed Adventures:
"The Pale Lady's Tomb" (Winterhold, undead/supernatural)
"Thornheart Grove" (Riften area, nature corruption)
[Additional adventures from your Seeds Bank as needed]
The Trigger for Act II
When the party reaches Expert Tier (typically after earning 4-5 AP), the Royal Summons arrives. This can happen:
At an inn where they're staying
Delivered by a courier who tracks them down
Posted on a bounty board in a major city
The Summons: A formal invitation bearing the seal of High King Torygg, requesting their presence at the Blue Palace in Solitude for a matter of "utmost importance to the realm."
Player Choice: The party can accept or decline this summons. If they decline, the main quest does not occur, and the world continues to deteriorate without their intervention.

Act II: The King's Mandate
Chapter 1: The Skyrim Wardens
Goal: Introduce all major NPCs and establish the party's new status, creating the foundation that will immediately crumble.
Scene 1: The Journey to Solitude
The party travels to Solitude on their own. They experience the city's grandeur, military presence, and the weight of being summoned by the High King himself.
Scene 2: The Throne Room - First Impressions
Location: The Blue Palace throne room
NPCs Present:
High King Torygg (genuine, pragmatic, concerned)
Jarl Elisif (supportive, present but quiet)
Falk Firebeard (cautious, scrutinizing)
The Rival (already present, standing apart)
The Rival's Introduction:
When the party enters, they see another figure already in audienceΓÇöa lone warrior of exceptional bearing. Torygg gestures to both the party and this stranger:
"I have summoned the finest independent operators in Skyrim. You," he indicates the party, "have proven yourselves through teamwork, adaptability, and consistent results across multiple holds. And you," he nods to the Rival, "have carved a legend through sheer, uncompromising skill. Alone, you've accomplished what most can only achieve with an entire company."
The Rival - First Impression:
Solo operator, supremely skilled
Quiet confidence bordering on arrogance
Brutally efficient reputation
Morally flexibleΓÇögets results regardless of cost
Not hostile, but not warmΓÇöprofessional and distant
Scene 3: The Offer
Torygg's Speech: Torygg explains his fears about dragons, ancient tombs opening, and Daedric cults while the Civil War consumes resources. He needs a group loyal to Skyrim itself, not to a political faction.
The Charter: He offers to charter them ALLΓÇöthe party and the RivalΓÇöas the founding members of "The Skyrim Wardens."
The Terms:
A generous annual stipend (paid upfront for the first year)
Legal authority to act in the High King's name
A dedicated cart driver on the royal payroll
Their first official mission
The Rival's Response: The Rival accepts with a curt nod. He sees the strategic value but remains aloof. This is a contract, not a brotherhood.
Scene 4: Meeting Old Bjorn
Location: The Solitude stables
Torygg personally introduces the party (and the Rival) to their new driver:
"This is Bjorn. He's driven trade routes across Skyrim for decades. Reliable, discreet, and he knows the land better than most Jarls know their own holds. His salary is provided by the Crown. His service is yours."
Old Bjorn - Initial Impression:
A man in his sixties, weathered but healthy
Calm, competent demeanor
Surprisingly charismatic in a quiet way
Greets both the party and the Rival with equal, professional courtesy
"Well then. Where are we headed?"
The Cart: A sturdy, enclosed wagon suitable for long journeys and sleeping during Long Rests when parked safely.
Scene 5: The First Mission
Torygg gives them their assignment: "Travel to Kynesgrove. We've received reports of a dragon attack and strange activity at an old burial mound. Investigate and handle the threat."
The newly formed WardensΓÇöparty, Rival, and BjornΓÇödepart Solitude together.

Chapter 2: The Kynesgrove Mission
Goal: Demonstrate the Rival's superior power level and create tension within the temporary alliance.
The Journey
The trip to Kynesgrove is the party's first extended time with both the Rival and Bjorn.
Bjorn's Role:
Handles all logistics smoothly
Shares stories and local knowledge
Keeps mood light despite tension
Treats everyone equally
The Rival's Behavior:
Professional but distant
Doesn't share around the campfire
Scouts ahead alone
Clearly used to working solo
Respects competence, dismisses weakness
The Investigation
What They Find:
Kynesgrove is devastated
Survivors describe a massive black dragon (Alduin) arriving
The dragon resurrected another dragon (Sahloknir) from a burial mound
Sahloknir is still in the area, hunting survivors
Evidence of Dragon Cult activity
The Confrontation with Sahloknir
This should be a challenging Expert-tier encounter designed to showcase the Rival.
The Rival's Performance:
Secures the most kills
Solves tactical problems with brutal efficiency
Uses morally questionable methods (uses civilians as bait, destroys property for advantage)
Demonstrates a level of skill currently beyond the party
His methods WORK but create tension
The Result:
Sahloknir is defeated (but not permanently destroyedΓÇöno one can absorb his soul)
Mission success, but uncomfortable dynamics
The Rival proves he's the most powerful member of the Wardens
Party feels overshadowed but respected for their teamwork
The Return Journey
The Wardens return to Solitude, mission accomplished but with a tense internal dynamic. The Rival remains professional but makes it clear he could have done this alone.
Old Bjorn tries to smooth tensions with conversation, but even he can't fully bridge the gap between the collaborative party and the lone wolf Rival.

Chapter 3: The World Turned Upside Down
Goal: Deliver the devastating news and trigger the schism.
Scene 1: Arrival at Solitude
The Wardens arrive back at Solitude to report their success. The atmosphere is immediately wrong:
Guards on high alert
Flags at half-mast
People speaking in frightened whispers
Tension in the air
Scene 2: The News
Before they can reach the Blue Palace, they learn the truth from panicked citizens:
"You haven't heard? Ulfric Stormcloak came to the city. He challenged the High King to a duel. The old way, single combat. But he used the VoiceΓÇöthe Thu'um. He shouted Torygg apart. The High King is dead. Ulfric fled. The city is in chaos."
Additional Details:
It happened mere hours after the Wardens departed
Solitude is in mourning
Jarl Elisif is devastated
No one knows if Torygg's decrees will be honored
The Civil War is about to explode
Scene 3: The Schism
Location: The courtyard outside the Blue Palace or the Winking Skeever
The Wardens gather to process this news. The Rival's reaction is immediate and harsh:
The Rival's Declaration:
"Our patron is dead. The charter is worthlessΓÇöa dead man's dream. Skyrim is about to tear itself apart, and you want to honor a scrap of paper?"
He looks at the party with something between pity and contempt.
"You're good. I won't deny that. But you're not good enough to survive what's coming. Working with you will only slow me down and get us all killed. I've always worked alone. I should have kept it that way."
He takes his share of the payment and prepares to leave.
"I'll save Skyrim my way. You do what you think is right. Maybe we'll meet again when this is over."
The Party's Choice: The party can try to convince him to stay (extremely difficult social challenge) or let him go. Either way, the Rival leaves as a free agent.
Old Bjorn's Reaction: Quiet and pragmatic: "Well. That complicates things. I'm still on the Solitude payroll, far as I know. Jarl Elisif controls the treasury now. Your charter is legal and signed. But you're on your own for funding beyond what you've already been given."
Scene 4: The New Reality
The Party's Situation:
Their charter is legitimate but politically controversial
They have their initial stipend but no promise of more funds
Their most powerful member has abandoned them
Their patron is dead before he could provide any support
The world is about to explode into war
They must fund future operations through quest rewards
Conclusion of Act II: The party is left standing in a city in mourning, holding the last will of a murdered king, abandoned by their strongest ally. They must choose: honor Torygg's vision alone, or walk away from this doomed endeavor.
The Rival vanishes into Skyrim, beginning his own parallel quest for power.

Act III: The Mortal Limit (Parallel Journeys)
Overview
The Wardens and the Rival pursue the same goalΓÇösaving Skyrim from the dragon crisisΓÇöbut through radically different approaches. Their paths run parallel, occasionally intersecting, but always diverging. Both will discover they cannot win through conventional means, but their responses to this revelation will define them.
Session Range: Approximately Sessions 9-32 (Dragon Cult Tiers 1-3)

The Party's Path: The Road of Wisdom
Phase 1: Investigation and Discovery (Sessions 9-16)
The Party's Focus:
Continue investigating the dragon threat
Hunt Dragon Priests to gather intelligence
Build alliances with Jarls and other factions
Fund themselves through quest rewards
Key Milestone: First Dragon Priest
The party defeats their first Dragon Priest (suggested: Vokun at High Gate Ruins). This is a full 5-section dungeon:
Critical Intelligence Recovered:
Maps showing the Throat of the World as central to draconic power
References to "the Master" and "the World-Eater"
Evidence that Dragon Priests are coordinating
Mentions of the "Greybeards" as masters of the Voice
Rival Sightings: During this phase, the party hears rumors or sees evidence of the Rival's parallel work:
"A lone warrior cleared out Forelhost single-handedly"
Finding a Dragon Priest's lair already looted
Rival visible in the distance at a Word Wall
Merchants mention a dangerous solo operator asking about ancient texts
The Rival is always one step ahead or one step behind, never quite catching up.
Phase 2: The Pilgrimage (Sessions 17-24)
The Journey to High Hrothgar:
The party's investigation points them to the Greybeards. They undertake the pilgrimage up the 7,000 Steps.
The Difficulty Gate: Convincing the Greybeards
Master Arngeir initially refuses to help:
"We await the Dovahkiin. You are not them. The affairs of the world below are not our concern."
The Party Must:
Present evidence (Dragon Priest masks, intelligence)
Make philosophical arguments about the Way of the Voice
Demonstrate restraint and genuine wisdom
Prove they seek knowledge, not power
The Breakthrough:
After significant effort (potentially multiple attempts), Arngeir relents:
"My master senses a wound in the prophecy. The Dovahkiin has not come, yet the signs are unmistakable. Your arrival may be consequence, not destiny. We will share what we know."
The Wisdom and the Wall:
Arngeir reveals:
The history of Alduin the World-Eater
The necessity of the Dragonrend Shout
The terrible truth: mastering it would take mortals decades
They do not have decades
The Unreadable Key:
Arngeir offers one final hope: an Elder Scroll may hold knowledge of how the ancient heroes defeated Alduin. But he warns that mortals cannot read it without risking madness or death.
Phase 3: The Quest for the Scroll (Sessions 25-32)
The Dwemer Ruins:
The party undertakes a perilous multi-session expedition:
Through Alftand's frozen halls
Into the alien landscape of Blackreach
To the Tower of Mzark
The Prize and the Problem:
They retrieve the Elder Scroll (Dragon) and return to the Greybeards triumphant.
Arngeir confirms the devastating truth: "Without a Dragon Soul to anchor your mind, attempting to read this will destroy you. You have achieved the impossible, and yet... it is not enough."
Conclusion of the Party's Act III:
The party has done everything right. They've proven their heroism, earned the trust of the Greybeards, and recovered a legendary artifact. But they are fundamentally, biologically incapable of using it. They are at a complete dead end.

The Rival's Path: The Road of Power
Phase 1: The Shortcut (Sessions 9-16)
The Rival's Focus (Off-Screen):
Also hunting Dragon Priests, but for personal gain
Seeking forbidden knowledge about transcending mortality
Researching ways to "become Dragonborn"
Growing increasingly ruthless and isolated
What the Party Notices:
Rumors of his brutal efficiency
Evidence of his growing obsession with power
Looted ruins and defeated enemies left in his wake
Reports of him interrogating scholars and cultists
The Rival's Discovery:
While the party pursues wisdom, the Rival uncovers forbidden texts in a Dragon Priest's lairΓÇöreferences to Mankar Camoran and the soul-carving ritual. He recognizes this as the shortcut he needs.
Phase 2: The Dark Quest (Sessions 17-24)
The Rival's Focus (Off-Screen):
Hunting for Mehrunes' Razor
Seeking a Lorkhan-touched ritual site
Gathering the necessary sacrificial knowledge
Growing more isolated and desperate
What the Party Notices:
Reports of the Rival becoming more dangerous
Rumors of him attacking Daedric cultists
Sightings near known Daedric shrines
A sense that he's pursuing something dark
The Parallel:
While the party climbs the mountain to seek wisdom from the Greybeards, the Rival descends into darkness to seek power from the Daedra.
Phase 3: The Transformation (Sessions 25-32)
The Ritual (Off-Screen):
During the same period the party is in Blackreach, the Rival completes his quest. He performs the soul-carving ritual and becomes a False Dragonborn.
What the Party Experiences:
When the Rival completes the ritual, there should be signs:
A tremor in the magical world
The Greybeards sense a "great and terrible power" awakening
Dark omens and disturbed wildlife
A feeling of wrongness in the air
Arngeir's Warning:
"Something has happened. A mortal has done something... unnatural. I sense a Dragon Soul where there should be none, but it is... hollow. Corrupted. This is a grave omen."
Conclusion of the Rival's Act III:
The Rival has achieved what he sought. He is now a False Dragonborn, possessing the power to absorb dragon souls and learn Shouts. But the ritual has carved away his empathy, his compassion, his humanity. He is a hollow forgery of what he once wasΓÇömore powerful, but fundamentally less.

